# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1932-winter-olympics] The **1932 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **III Olympic Winter Games** and commonly known as **Lake Placid 1932**, were a winter multi-sport event in the United States, held in Lake Placid, New York, United States.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1932-winter-olympics] The games opened on February 4 and closed on February 13.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1932-winter-olympics] It was the first time the Winter Games were held outside of Europe and the first of four Winter Olympics held in the United States; Lake Placid hosted again in 1980.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1932-winter-olympics] The games were awarded to Lake Placid in part by the efforts of Godfrey Dewey, head of the Lake Placid Club and son of Melvil Dewey, inventor of the Dewey Decimal System.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1932-winter-olympics] California also had a bid for the 1932 Winter Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1932-winter-olympics] William May Garland, president of the California X Olympiad Association, wanted the games to take place in Wrightwood and Big Pines, California.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1932-winter-olympics] The world's largest ski jump at the time was constructed in Big Pines for the event, but the games were ultimately awarded to Lake Placid.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1932-winter-olympics] The practice of awarding Olympic medals at podium ceremonies was established at the 1932 Winter Olympics, based on pedestals used at the 1930 British Empire Games, as proposed by Melville Marks Robinson.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1932-winter-olympics] Medals were awarded in 14 events contested in 4 sports (7 disciplines).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1932-winter-olympics] The Games also included events in three demonstration sports.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1932-winter-olympics] Athletes from 17 nations competed in these Games, down from 25 nations at the previous Games in 1928.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1932-winter-olympics] Argentina, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, Luxembourg, Mexico, the Netherlands, and Yugoslavia did not send athletes to Lake Placid.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The **1964 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **IX Olympic Winter Games** (German: *IX.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Olympische Winterspiele*) and commonly known as **Innsbruck 1964** (Austro-Bavarian: *Innschbruck 1964*), were a winter multi-sport event which was celebrated in Innsbruck, Austria, from January 29 to February 9, 1964.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The city was already an Olympic candidate, unsuccessfully bidding to host the 1960 Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Innsbruck won the 1964 Games bid, defeating the cities of Calgary in Canada and Lahti in Finland.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The sports venues, many of which were built for the Games, were located within a radius of 20 km (12 mi) around Innsbruck.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Games included 1,091 athletes from 36 nations, which was a record for the Winter Games at the time.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Athletes participated in six sports and ten disciplines which bring together a total of thirty-four official events, seven more than the 1960 Winter Olympic Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The luge made its debut on the Olympic program.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Three Asian nations made their Winter Games debut: North Korea, India and Mongolia.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Soviet Union broke the record for the most gold and overall medals at a single Winter Olympics, with eleven and twenty five respectively, and finished first in the medal table.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The USSR was followed by Austria, the host country, which won twelve medals, four of which were gold.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Soviet athletes Lidia Skoblikova won all four women's races of speed skating and Klavdiya Boyarskikh won all three events of cross-country skiing.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Swedish cross-country skier Sixten Jernberg, a three-time medalist at these Games, became the first athlete to collect nine medals at the Winter Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In alpine skiing, the French sisters Christine and Marielle Goitschel each obtained a gold and a silver medal.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Before the Games, the Austrian army was mobilized to deal with the lack of snow.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] They brought thousands of cubic meters of it from Brenner Pass, close to the Italian border.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Olympic Winter Games was held for a second time at Innsbruck in 1976.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Olympic Torch was carried by Joseph Rieder, a former alpine skier who had participated in the 1956 Winter Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Games were affected by the deaths of Australian alpine skier Ross Milne and British luge slider Kazimierz Kay-Skrzypeski, during training, and by the deaths, three years earlier, of the entire United States figure skating team and family members.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The city of Innsbruck submitted its first Olympic bid in the 1950s to host the 1960 Winter Olympic Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Austrians had a convincing bid and were viewed as the favorites to host the games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] However, in the second round of the vote the members of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) selected the American city of Squaw Valley due to its ambitious designs.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] A month later, the Innsbruck authorities decided to enter a bid again for the 1964 Winter Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] On 26 May 1959, during the 55th session of the (IOC) in Munich, West Germany, the Austrians were selected in a landslide for the Games with 49 votes in the first round, ahead of Calgary (Canada), which obtained 9 votes and Lahti (Finland), which did not receive a vote.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Despite the construction of the Berlin Wall by East Germany in 1961, which increased tensions between East and West and the fact that the East Germans wanted to have their own team, the IOC managed to maintain the United Team of Germany for the third consecutive Olympiad.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In the 1960s, the IOC also discussed the Olympic participation of South Africa, a country immersed in the apartheid regime.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] During the Games in Innbruck, the IOC President Avery Brundage announced that the country would not be able to participate in the 1964 Summer Olympics because of its policy of racial segregation in sport.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] On the other hand, several African countries which had become independent joined the Olympic movement: the national Olympic committees of Algeria, of Congo, from Nigeria and Sierra Leone were recognized by the IOC during the session held during the Innsbruck Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The number of IOC member nations increased to 114.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In addition, the Innsbruck Games were used for the dissemination of political messages.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Five Iranian students were arrested after marching with banners hostile to the shah.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Twenty other Iranians, who demonstrated for the release of prisoners in their country, were also imprisoned.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Organizing Committee of the IX Winter Olympics in Innsbruck 1964 was formed on 2 June 1959.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Heinrich Drimmel, President of the Austrian Olympic Committee and Federal Minister of Education, was elected as its president and Friedl Wolfgang was elected as its secretary-general.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Innsbruck Games cost around one billion schillings, or 40 million US dollars distributed among the organizing committee, the Austrian state, the Land of Tyrol and the city of Innsbruck.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The organizers tried to reduce the expenses related to the provisional elements, and to invest more money for the facilities which would continue to be used after the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Olympiaeisstadion costs 75 million schillings, the renovation of the Bergisel Ski Jump 15 million and the Olympic Sliding Centre Innsbruck 10 million.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The development of ski slopes, cross-country skiing and biathlon required a total of 29 million.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Olympic village, intended to become a leisure center, costs 174 million.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] A total of 225 million was invested to renovate and develop the road network in the region.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The 1964 edition was the third time that the Winter Games were broadcast on television and the second time that exclusive broadcasting rights were sold.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] This was a substantial increase: where they were US$50,000 in 1960, the broadcast rights yielded US$937,000 in 1964, which was approximately 24 million schillings.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The American channel ABC paid nearly 15.4 million schillings, or 64 per cent of the broadcast rights revenue.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Eurovision network spent around 7.6 million for 16 countries, the Soviet television 600,000 Rbls and the Intervision network US$550,000 for six countries in Western Europe.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The CTV Television Network paid CA$5,000 for the exclusive broadcast rights in Canada.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Games were held over twelve days, from January 29 to February 9.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Thirty-four events were on the program, an increase from the twenty-seven at Squaw Valley four years earlier.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Three luge events (individual men and women, doubles men) were included in the Olympic program.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Bobsled, which was absent from the 1960 Games due to the cost of building the track, returned to the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Ski jumping was divided into two events (small and large hill) and the women's 5-kilometer was added in cross-country skiing.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Ice stock sport (Eisstockschießen), a variant of curling popular in Alpine countries, was a demonstration sport as in Garmisch-Partenkirchen in 1936.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In total, 1,073,000 people attend the various events.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The disciplines which attracted the most spectators were alpine skiing and ice hockey.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] † The numeral indicates the number of event finals for each sport held that day.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In the weeks leading up to the Games, temperatures often rose above zero degrees Celsius due to the foehn, a hot, dry wind.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] There was no major snowfall for seven weeks, and the rain melted snow and ice at sports venues.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] This was the first time in around a century that the snowfall had been so low in Tyrol.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Two weeks before the start of the Games, thousands of Austrian soldiers were mobilized to transport by truck 40,000m3 of snow from the Brenner Pass, close to the Italian border, and spread it by hand on the ski slopes.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] 20,000m3 of snow was built up and 20,000 blocks of ice were transported to the bobsleigh and toboggan run.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Opening Ceremony took place on January 29 at the Bergisel Ski Jump stadium in front of approximately 50,000 spectators.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Games were opened by the President of Austria Adolf Schärf.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The bobsledder Paul Aste took the Olympic oath.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Aste modified the oath slightly: instead of saying "for the glory of sport and the honor of our countries", he replaced the word "country" with "teams" to remove the nationalist elements of the oath.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] This was the first time that the Olympic flame of the Winter Games has been lit in front of the Temple of Hera in Olympia, Greece.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In the stadium, the alpine skier Josef Rieder lit the cauldron.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Tyrolean orchestras performed during the ceremony.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The biathlon made its second Olympic appearance.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] As in 1960, the only event contested was a 20-kilometer cross-country ski race with four shooting ranges of 100 to 250 meters.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Soviet athlete Vladimir Melanin, a heavy favorite, won the event.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] This was the first time he did not miss any of his twenty shots in a major competition.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] His compatriot Aleksandr Privalov, who also had a clean shoot, was second by more than three minutes and the Norwegian Olav Jordet, who missed a target, won the bronze medal.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Finn Veikko Hakulinen was the fastest, but missed six shots and finished 15th.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The bobsleigh was not on the program for the 1960 Winter Olympic Games, at Squaw Valley in the United States, because of the low number of crews and the cost of building the track.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In 1964, bobsleigh events made a comeback and were contested on the Olympic Sliding Centre Innsbruck.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Neither of the two Olympic champion teams, Great Britain and Canada, had a track in their country at the time.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] During the first round of the two-man event, the bobsleigh of the British Robin Dixon and Tony Nash was damaged and the competition's favorite, the Italian Eugenio Monti, lent them an axle bolt.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] After two rounds, the British beat the two Italian teams.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] After the third set, the Italians Sergio Zardini and Romano Bonagura beat Dixon and Nash by just five hundredths of a second.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Finally, Dixon and Nash become Olympic champions with 12 hundredths ahead of silver medalists Zardini and Bonagura and 73 over third, Eugenio Monti and Sergio Siorpaes.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] This is the only time in history that the British have been Olympic bobsleigh champions.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] After the Games, Monti received the first International Fair Play Committee Pierre de Coubertin World Trophy for his sportsmanship towards the British team.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Canadians surprised in the four-man bobsleigh event.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] As the country competed for the first time in the Olympic bobsleigh events, the pilot's team Vic Emery won the first round, breaking the track record, and increased his lead in the following three rounds.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Canada won gold by more than a second ahead of Erwin Thaler 's Austrian bobsleigh and Eugenio Monti' s Italian bobsleigh.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Nordic combined event took place in the village of Seefeld in Tirol.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] On the first day, the competitors did three jumps and the two best results are recorded.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The next day, they did a 15-kilometer cross-country ski race.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The final ranking was established with a new points system.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The reigning Olympic champion, the German Georg Thoma, was first ahead of the Norwegian Tormod Knutsen and the Soviet Nikolay Kiselyov after the jumps.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Knutsen needed to beat Thoma by at least twelve seconds in the cross-country ski race to pass him, which he did, winning by 1.33 and becoming Olympic champion.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Thoma, who had wax problems and fell twice during the race, was third, just 0.16 points behind Kisseliov after a tenth-place finish in cross-country skiing.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The matches of ice hockey were played in the Olympiaeisstadion and the Messehalle.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The sixteen participating teams first played a match to determine their group for the rest of the competition: group A (which allocates places 1 to 8) or group B (places 9 to 16).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Then, each team faced the other seven of its group.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In Group A, the Soviet favorites won their seven matches and became Olympic champions.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The tournament was actually very close since in the last game, the Soviets were losing 2–1 against Canada after two periods to finally win 3–2; if Canada had won they would have taken the gold medal.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Behind the Soviet Union, three teams had five wins and two losses: Canada, Czechoslovakia and Sweden.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] These three teams were ranked by goal difference with Sweden receiving silver, Czechoslovakia bronze and Canada finishing fourth.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Canadians, who were not satisfied with the method used to decide between Sweden and Czechoslovakia, boycotted the medal ceremony.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Luge was a popular sport in the Alpine countries, the first competition of which dates back to 1831.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The first international event was organized in 1928.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The IOC decided in 1954 to include luge in the program of the 1964 Games to replace the skeleton, because there was only one track adapted to this sport: the Cresta Run of Saint-Moritz in Switzerland.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Three events were contested at the Games: individual for men and women and two for men.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Some commentators believed that luge was too dangerous a sport to enter the Olympic program.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The death of Poland-born British luger Kazimierz Kay-Skrzypeski during a test run two weeks before the start of the Games helped reinforce this position.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The luge events were dominated by the Germans, who took five out of six medals individually.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] During the men's individual event, a German trio dominated the competition: the 1962 world champion Thomas Köhler as well as Klaus Bonsack and Hans Plenk were the top three in each of the first three rounds, won respectively by Köhler, Bonsack and again Köhler.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Finally, Köhler became an Olympic champion, 27 hundredths of a second ahead of Bonsack and 3.38 seconds ahead of Plenk.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The German Ilse Geisler, world champion in 1962 and 1963, was the favorite in the women's event.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] However, it was her compatriot Ortrun Enderlein who won the first three races.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Geiser took a lot of risks in the last heat and made a big mistake, letting Enderlein win again.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Enderlein became Olympic champion, almost three seconds ahead of Geisler.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Austrian Helene Thurner won the bronze medal.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The doubles event, which takes place over two rounds, was dominated by the Austrians.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Indeed, Josef Feistmantl and Manfred Stengl won the first round ahead of Reinhold Senn and Helmut Thaler.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The latter won the second round without worrying Feistmantl and Stengl, crowned Olympic champions.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Italians Walter Ausserdorfer and Sigisfredo Mair are bronze medalists.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The figure skating events were held at the Olympiaeisstadion.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Individually, men and women performed a free skate and compulsory figures while, for the last time in an international competition, the couples only presented one program.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Computers are used for refereeing, which is new to the Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The data processing system provided by the company IBM allows scores to be announced instantly.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In addition to figure skating, information is sent to a data center at University of Innsbruck from eleven other facilities.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In the men's event, the German Manfred Schnelldorfer became Olympic champion by winning each round.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Frenchman Alain Calmat, slightly favored before the Olympics, finished in second place.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The American Scott Allen won the bronze medal, just two days before his fifteenth birthday.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] He thus became the youngest medalist in the history of the Winter Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The big favorite in the women's event, the Dutch Sjoukje Dijkstra, easily became Olympic champion.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] She is in fact placed in the first row by the nine judges.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In front of the Dutch royal family, she won the first Dutch gold medal at the Winter Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Austrian Regine Heitzer was the silver medalist with a small lead over the Canadian Petra Burka.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Soviets Ludmila Belousova and Oleg Protopopov, a married couple, narrowly won the pair event ahead of the German Marika Kilius and Hans-Jürgen Bäumler.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The bronze medals went to Canadians Debbi Wilkes and Guy Revell.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In 1966, Kilius and Bäumler had to return their medals because of a professional contract signed before the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Canadians received the silver medal and the Americans Vivian and Ronald Joseph, initially fourth, received the bronze medal.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In 1987, however, the IOC decided to restore the medals of the German couple.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The results then plunged into confusion since the different rankings did not indicate the same information.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In 2013, the IOC clarified that the Soviets had the gold medal, the Canadians and the Germans shared the silver medal and the Americans the bronze medal.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] These were the official results since 1987.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The speed skating events took place on an outdoor track set up around the Olympiaeisstadion.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] While the Soviets dominated the women's events, the men's podiums are more international.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The American Terry McDermott, who was not one of the favorites, won the men's 500 meters setting a new Olympic record.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Taking part in his first international competition, he borrowed skates from his trainer Leo Freisinger.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Three athletes, including the favorite of the event Yevgeny Grishin, shared second place.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Soviet Ants Antson won the gold medal in the 1,500 meters, ahead of the Dutch Kees Verkerk and the Norwegian Villy Haugen, after a very close race.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Norwegians score a hat-trick in the 5,000 meters.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Knut Johannesen is a gold medalist beating the Olympic record just two-tenths ahead of Per Ivar Moe.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Finally, the Swede Jonny Nilsson won the 10,000 meters ahead of the Norwegians Fred Anton Maier and Knut Johannesen.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] This race was controversial because Nilsson was one of the few to skate before the wind picked up, and enjoyed better ice than most of the other competitors.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Soviet Lidia Skoblikova won all four races at the 1963 world championships.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] A big favorite, she reproduced the same performance at the 1964 Olympic Games, breaking the Olympic record each time.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] She thus becomes the first athlete to win four gold medals in one edition of the Winter Games and the first, after her two titles in 1960, to accumulate six gold medals in several editions.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Skoblikova first won the 500 meters ahead of her compatriots Irina Yegorova and Tatyana Sidorova.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] On 1,000 meters, she was ahead of Irina Iegorova and the Finn Kaija Mustonen.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] She dominated the 1,500 meters, with a time almost three seconds ahead of Mustonen.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Finally, Skoblikova took the 5,000 meters with almost four seconds.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The North Korean Han Pil-hwa, unknown before the Games, created a surprise: tied with Skoblikova halfway through the course, she was ended up tied for second with the Soviet Valentina Stenina.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] North Korea participated in the Games for the first time; that was the country's first Olympic medal.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Upon her return home, Skoblikova was made a member of the Communist Party and became the first woman to win the title of Soviet Sportsman of the Year.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] For the first time in 1964, two ski jumping events were contested at the Olympic Games: small hill, contested at Toni-Seelos-Olympiaschanze and big hill, which takes place at Bergisel Ski Jump.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] They have a construction point of 70 and 90 meters respectively.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Athletes jump three times and their two best results count in each event.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Czechoslovak Josef Matouš surprised many by winning the first round of the normal hill while the Finn Veikko Kankkonen, who was among the favorites, was only twenty-ninth.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Kankkonen had the best jump of the competition in the second set, at 80 meters, and the Norwegian Toralf Engan took the lead.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] After the third round, Kankkonen who again produced a good jump, became Olympic champion.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Toralf Engan was second while young Norwegian Torgeir Brandtzæg took third place.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In the first round of the big hill, Veikko Kankkonen took the lead in front of Toralf Engan with a jump of 95.5 meters.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Engan took the first place after the second jump, while Kankkonen and Brandtzæg followed closely behind.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Brandtzæg finished with a good jump unlike his two rivals.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The medalists are the same as for the normal hill, but this time Engan is Olympic champion ahead of Kankkonen.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Most alpine skiing events were held at Axamer Lizum, with the men's downhill being held at the Patscherkofel (above Igls).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Three events were on the program for men and women: downhill, giant slalom and slalom.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] For the first time at the Olympics, athletes were timed to the hundredth of a second.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The competition was held in mourning for the death of Australian Ross Milne, who crashed into a tree during downhill training.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Egon Zimmermann of Austria won the men's downhill, 74 hundredths of a second ahead of France's Léo Lacroix and 1.32 seconds over Wolfgang Bartels of Germany.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] For the last time at the Olympics, the men's giant slalom was held in a single round.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The French François Bonlieu won the race ahead of the Austrian favorites: Karl Schranz was second, and Josef Stiegler was third.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] For the first time, the Olympic slalom had a two-round qualifying phase.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The 25 best take part in the two final rounds which determine the ranking of the event.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Austrian officials tried to replace Josef Stiegler with Egon Zimmermann, but Stiegler competed in the slalom under public pressure.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Americans Billy Kidd and Jimmy Heuga, second and third respectively, won their country's first Olympic medals in alpine skiing.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In the women's downhill, the Austrians achieved the second treble in the history of the Winter Games in alpine skiing.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The favorite Christl Haas was Olympic champion, more than a second ahead of Edith Zimmermann and Traudl Hecher.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The technical events were dominated by two French women, the Goitschel sisters.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Marielle Goitschel, aged 18, won the first round of the slalom ahead of her sister Christine, one year her senior.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Christine was the fastest, however, in the second run.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] She won gold, ahead of Marielle, while the bronze medal was awarded to the American Jean Saubert.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Two days later, Christine Goitschel took the lead in the giant slalom.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] His time was then equaled by Jean Saubert.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Marielle Goitschel, the fourteenth skier to set off, was almost a second ahead of them however.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The eldest Goitschel finished first this time, while her sister shared second place with Saubert.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The cross-country skiing events took place near the village of Seefeld in Tirol.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The men competed as usual in individual over 15, 30 and 50 kilometer as well as in the 4 × 10 kilometer relay.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] On the other hand, women competed for the first time at the Olympic Games the 5 kilometer, introduced at the world championships in 1962, in addition to the 10 kilometer and the relay 3 × 5 kilometer.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Men's events started with the 30 kilometers.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Finn Eero Mäntyranta won the race ahead of the Norwegian Harald Grønningen and the Soviet Igor Voronchikhin.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Swede Sixten Jernberg, the favorite after his six Olympic medals obtained in 1956 and 1960, finished fifth.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Eight of the top nine athletes were Scandinavian.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In the 15 kilometer skied three days later, Eero Mäntyranta was once again crowned Olympic champion ahead of Harald Grønningen.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Sixten Jernberg wins bronze, his seventh Olympic medal.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Racing the day before his 35th birthday, Jernberg took the lead at the end of the 50 kilometer.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] He won gold, his eighth Olympic medal, finishing more than a minute ahead of his compatriot Assar Rönnlund.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The end of the relay 4 × 10 kilometer was a duel between the Finnish Eero Mäntyranta and the Swede Assar Rönnlund, who overtook the Soviet Pavel Kolchin one kilometer from the finish.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Sweden eventually won the event, eight seconds ahead of Finland and twelve over the Soviet Union.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Jernberg ended his Olympic career with nine medals including four gold, which was a new record.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Soviet skiers dominated the women's events as they won six of the seven possible medals.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In the 10 kilometer they achieved the treble as in 1960: Klavdiya Boyarskikh ahead Yevdokiya Mekshilo and Maria Gusakova.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] For the first time among women, non-European cross-country skiers took part in the Olympic Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The two North Koreans and the two Mongols, however, finished in the last four places.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Boyarskikh also won the very close Olympic 5 km, while Finland's Mirja Lehtonen surprised by taking second place.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Finally, the Soviets won the relay 3 × 5 kilometer for the first time.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] They were well ahead of the Swedes by two minutes and the Finns by three.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Klavdiya Boyarskikh wins his third gold medal at these Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] For the first time on games history, the Closing Ceremony was not held at the Olympic Stadium and in an indoor place, took place on February 9 at the Olympiaeisstadion.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The flags of Greece, the founding nation of the Olympic Games, Austria, the host country, and France, the host country of the next Games, were raised to the sound of the national anthems.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The President of the IOC Avery Brundage officially declared the Games closed before the extinction of the Olympic flame.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Fourteen of the thirty-six nations which participated in these Games won at least one medal, as detailed in the table below.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Already first in 1956 and 1960, the Soviet Union came far ahead of this table with twenty-five medals: eleven gold, eight silver and six bronze, a new record for both gold and total medals won at a single Winter Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The host country, ninth four years earlier, was second with twelve medals, including seven in alpine skiing.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Norway, fourth in 1964, came third with fifteen medals.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Soviets also dominated the ranking of the most medal-winning athletes as the speed skater Lidia Skoblikova and cross-country skier Klavdiya Boyarskikh came first and second.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Several sports venues were built especially for the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] New slopes for alpine skiing were developed near the village of Axamer Lizum, about twenty kilometers from Innsbruck.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] There is a bobsleigh and luge track in Igls, seven kilometers south of Innsbruck.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The runway, 1506 meters long, had 14 curves and a drop of 138 meters.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] For the first time at the Games, the bobsleigh track used artificial ice.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Olympiaeisstadion, an eleven thousand-seat ice rink completed in 1963 and located in the center of Innsbruck, hosted the competitions of figure skating and most games of ice hockey.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The other hockey matches were played at the Messehalle.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The speed skating ring, made of artificial ice, was installed outside the Olympiaeisstadion.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The ski jumping events were held on the Toni-Seelos-Olympiaschanze (normal hill) at Seefeld in Tirol and the Bergisel Ski Jump (big jump) in Innsbruck.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Bergisel ski jump, built in wood in 1920, was replaced by a concrete ski jump.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The cross-country skiing and biathlon tracks were located in Seefeld, like the small hill.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The opening ceremony was celebrated at the foot of the Bergisel ski jump while the closing ceremony took place at the Olympiaeisstadion.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] An Olympic Village consisting of eight eleven-storey buildings was built outside the city.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] A total of 36 nations sent athletes to Innsbruck, six more than in Squaw Valley in 1960.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The total number of athletes was 1,091, up from 665 four years earlier.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Mongolia, India and North Korea participated in the Winter Games for the first time.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Belgium, Greece, Iran, Romania and Yugoslavia returned to this competition after missing it in 1960.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] On the other hand, South Africa and New Zealand, which took part in Squaw Valley, did not compete in Innsbruck.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] Athletes from West Germany (FRG) and East Germany (GDR) competed together as Unified Team Germany from 1956 to 1964.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The number indicated in brackets is the number of athletes entered in the official events for each country.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] There were also several injuries which occurred prior to the event.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] In the 1970s, the American city of Denver, chosen to host the 1976 Winter Olympics, rejected the bid after a statewide referendum.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] About ten cities applied to take over the Games and Innsbruck was selected.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The main reasons for this choice were the venues built for the 1964 Games, which kept costs down, and their good organization during the 1964 Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1964-winter-olympics] The Olympic venues subsequently hosted various sports competitions such as the Four Hills Tournament, Bobsleigh and Luge World Cup events, the Winter Universiade and the Ice Hockey World Championship in 2005 and the first Winter Youth Olympic Games in 2012.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] The **1972 British Columbia general election** for the Canadian province of British Columbia was held to elect members of the Legislative Assembly of British Columbia.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] The election was called on July 24, 1972, and held on August 30, 1972.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] The new legislature met for the first time on October 17, 1972.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] David Barrett led the social democratic New Democratic Party to victory, winning a majority government.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] The Social Credit Party, led by Premier W.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] Bennett, were defeated after governing British Columbia since the 1952 election.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] Social Credit's share of the popular vote fell by over 15 percentage points, and the party lost 28 of the seats it had won in the previous election.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] The Liberal Party held onto its five seats, while the Progressive Conservative Party, under the leadership of Derrill Warren, returned to the legislature for the first time since the 1953 election by winning two seats.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] In four ridings and part of a fifth, a referendum was held on the question of daylight saving time and which time zone to use concurrently with the election.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] Social Credit ran a lackluster campaign beset by gaffes.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] A week before the general election, cabinet minister Phil Gaglardi remarked to a newspaper that Bennett would resign after the election, calling him "an old man who doesn't understand what is happening with the young people of this province".
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] The remark proved damaging, bringing the issue of whether Bennett and his party were worn out after 20 years in office to the forefront of the campaign.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] A pre-campaign visit by Bennett and his cabinet to New Westminster turned violent after they were confronted by demonstrators, who injured eight ministers, a melee for which Bennett tried to blame Barrett.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] Shortly after the Social Credit campaign started, Bennett was tricked into shaking hands with current Progressive Conservative leader Derril Warren in front of a photographer from *The Province*.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] After the photograph, depicting a smiling Warren and scowling Bennett, was published on *The Province'*s front page, Bennett spent the rest of the campaign antagonising the media, refusing to tell reporters where he was appearing.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] Barrett benefited from his youth, allowing the media to contrast him with the aged Bennett, and ran a campaign focused on "people issues" such as urban transit, public auto insurance, and increased royalties from the province's timber and minerals industries.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] Although Bennett's campaign had been lacklustre, no commentators anticipated the party's loss.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-british-columbia-general-election] The resulting NDP majority came as a surprise.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum] The **Denver Winter Olympics referendum** was held in November 1972 following the awarding to Denver of the 1976 Winter Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum] The selection process for the 1976 Winter Olympics consisted of four bids, and saw Denver, Colorado, United States, selected ahead of Sion, Switzerland; Tampere, Finland; and Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum] The selection was made at the 70th IOC Session in Amsterdam on 12 May 1970.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum] In a 1972 referendum, voters in Colorado rejected funding for the Olympics, the only time a city awarded the Olympics rejected them.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum] Denver officially withdrew on 15 November, and Sion, the runner-up, also declined to host the Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum] The IOC then offered the Olympics to Whistler, British Columbia, Canada, but they too declined owing to a change of government following elections.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum] Whistler went on to be associated with neighbouring Vancouver's successful bid for the 2010 Winter Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum] Salt Lake City, Utah, offered to host, then pulled its bid and was replaced by Lake Placid, New York.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum] Still reeling from the Denver rejection, the IOC declined and on 5 February 1973, selected Innsbruck, Austria, which had hosted nine years earlier in 1964.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum] In autumn 1974, Lake Placid was awarded the 1980 Winter Olympics, its second; Salt Lake hosted in 2002 and will again in 2034.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum] To date, Colorado has yet to host an Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum] Richard Lamm was an obscure state legislator from Denver when he led the campaign; after the referendum he was elected to three terms as governor, serving from 1975 to 1987.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum] Within three months, Innsbruck, Austria was selected as the replacement city, hosting the Winter Olympics for the second time, after 1964.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-winter-olympics] The **1972 Winter Olympics**, officially the **XI Olympic Winter Games** and commonly known as **Sapporo 1972**, were a winter multi-sport event held from February 3 to 13, 1972, in Sapporo, Hokkaido Prefecture, Japan.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-winter-olympics] It was the first Winter Olympic Games to take place outside Europe and North America.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-winter-olympics] Sapporo first won the rights to host the 1940 Winter Olympics, but Japan resigned as the Games' host after its 1937 invasion of China.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-winter-olympics] All the cities awarded Games that were cancelled due to war have since hosted the Games (London, Tokyo, Helsinki, Sapporo and Cortina d'Ampezzo).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-winter-olympics] Sapporo competed with Banff, Lahti, and Salt Lake City.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-winter-olympics] The Games were awarded at the 64th IOC Session in Rome, Italy, on April 26, 1966.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-winter-olympics] In preparation, the Japanese constructed new largescale facilities at Sapporo and conducted a trial run a full year in advance of the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-winter-olympics] An international sport week was held in February, 1971, to assess the city's preparations as well as "to test its civic mettle and hospitality", and this effort was acclaimed by Olympic observers as "a complete success".
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-winter-olympics] The development of new infrastructure proved to be a huge boon for the Sapporo economy: by the time of the Games, the national government had invested some US$500 million in upgrades, including a new subway.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-winter-olympics] The Games' organizers themselves turned a healthy profit in part because they arranged a record $8.47 million for broadcasting rights with American companies.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-winter-olympics] 1 New facilities constructed in preparation for the Olympic Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-winter-olympics] 2 Existing facilities modified or refurbished in preparation for the Olympic Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-winter-olympics] There were 35 events contested in 6 sports (10 disciplines).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-winter-olympics] 35 nations participated in the 1972 Winter Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-winter-olympics] The Republic of China (commonly known as Taiwan) and the Philippines participated in their first Winter Olympic Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1972-winter-olympics] These are the top eleven nations that won medals at these Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] The **1976 Winter Olympics**, officially known as the **XII Olympic Winter Games** (German: *XII.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] Olympische Winterspiele*, French: *XIIes Jeux olympiques d'hiver*) and commonly known as **Innsbruck 1976** (Austro-Bavarian: *Innschbruck 1976*), were a winter multi-sport event celebrated in Innsbruck, Austria, from February 4 to 15, 1976.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] The games were awarded to Innsbruck after Denver, the original host city, withdrew in 1972.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] This was the second time the Tyrolean capital had hosted the Winter Olympics, having first done so in 1964.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] The cities of Denver, Colorado, United States; Sion, Switzerland; Tampere, Finland; and Vancouver (with most events near Mount Garibaldi), British Columbia, Canada, made bids for the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] The host was decided at the 69th IOC meeting in Amsterdam, Netherlands, on May 12, 1970.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] Denver planned to hold its games between February 12 and 22, 1976.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] In a statewide referendum on 7 November 1972, Colorado voters rejected funding for the games, and for the first (and only) time a city awarded the Winter Games rejected them.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] Denver officially withdrew on 15 November, and original runner-up Sion declined to host the Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] Afterwards, the IOC then offered the games to Whistler, British Columbia, Canada, but they too declined owing to a change of government following elections.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] Salt Lake City offered to host the games, then pulled its bid and was replaced by Lake Placid, New York.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] Still reeling from the Denver rejection, the IOC declined and on 4 February 1973, selected Innsbruck, Austria, which had hosted nine years earlier in 1964.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] The mascot of the 1976 Winter Olympics was Schneemann, a snowman in a red Tyrolean hat.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] Designed by Walter Pötsch, Schneeman was purported to represent the 1976 Games as the "Games of Simplicity".
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] It was also regarded as a good-luck charm, to avert the dearth of snow that had marred the 1964 Winter Olympics in Innsbruck.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] There was a second mascot called Sonnenweiberl ("sun wife").
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] There were 37 events contested in 6 sports (10 disciplines).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] 37 nations participated in the 1976 Winter Olympic Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] The games marked the final time the Republic of China (Taiwan) participated under the Republic of China flag and name.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] After most of the international community recognized the People's Republic of China as the legitimate government of all China, the ROC was forced to compete under the name Chinese Taipei, under an altered flag and to use its National Banner Song instead of its national anthem.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] Andorra and San Marino participated in their first Winter Olympic Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1976 Winter Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] In 1977, *White Rock*, the official documentary film about the Innsbruck 1976 Winter Olympics was released.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] The film was narrated by James Coburn, and directed by Tony Maylam.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] It was nominated for the Robert Flaherty Award (Feature Length Film, Documentary In Content) at the 30th British Academy Film Awards.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] The film's soundtrack was composed by English keyboardist Rick Wakeman.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1976-winter-olympics] His album, *White Rock* entered the UK Albums Chart on 12 February 1977, where it spent 9 weeks and reached number 14.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The **1980 Winter Olympics**, officially the **XIII Olympic Winter Games** and also known as **Lake Placid 1980**, were an international multi-sport event held from February 13 to 24, 1980, in Lake Placid, New York, United States.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Lake Placid was elected as the host city for the 1980 Winter Games at the 75th International Olympic Committee (IOC) Session in Vienna, Austria, in 1974.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] This marked the second time the Upstate New York village hosted the Winter Games, after 1932.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The only other candidate city to bid for the 1980 games, Vancouver–Garibaldi, withdrew before the final vote.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Some venues from the 1932 Games were renovated for use in the 1980 Games, and events were held at the Olympic Center, Whiteface Mountain, Mt.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Van Hoevenberg Olympic Bobsled Run, the Olympic Ski Jumps, the Cascade Cross Country Ski Center, and the Lake Placid High School Speed Skating Oval.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The Games were a success in terms of sport, but the organization was criticized because of numerous transport problems.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The 1980 Games were the last to take place in a city of less than 15,000 inhabitants.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The Lake Placid Winter Olympics brought together 1,072 athletes from 37 countries to take part in six sports and 10 disciplines comprising a total of 38 official events (one more than in 1976).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] People's Republic of China, Cyprus, and Costa Rica participated in the Winter Olympic Games for the first time.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] American speed skater Eric Heiden set the record for most medals for an athlete in one edition of the Winter Olympic Games after he medaled in all five speed skating events.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The Olympic ice hockey tournament saw the young American team defeat the heavily favored Soviet professionals in what became known as the *Miracle on Ice*, on their way to the gold medal.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] In the other disciplines, Soviet Nikolaj Zimjatov won three gold medals in cross-country skiing and the Liechtenstein skier Hanni Wenzel won her country's first two gold medals in alpine skiing.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The Soviet Union finished first in the medal standings, with ten gold medals, while East Germany won the most medals overall, 23.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The United States was third on both counts.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] After Lake Placid hosted the 1932 Olympic Winter Games, the community continued to bid on upcoming editions of the Games, submitting seven total bid attempts, including 1948, 1952, and 1956.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Three of these were supported by the United States Olympic Committee and presented to the International Olympic Committee: 1968, 1976, and 1980.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Until 1980, each of the bid attempts failed, either due to falling short of gaining support at the national level, or during the IOC vote.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] When Denver withdrew after being selected to host the 1976 Winter Games, the USOC initially supported Salt Lake City to replace Denver.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] But on January 26, 1973, the Salt Lake City bid collapsed due to unsecured financial backing and discontent by Utah residents.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Lake Placid and the USOC submitted a late bid to host the 1976 Games to the IOC in February 1973, as there was a risk that the selection process would be canceled due to the lack of interested parties.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The IOC selected Innsbruck, Austria, to host the 1976 Games in place of Denver, with Lake Placid finishing as the runner-up.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] IOC President Lord Killanin later stated that members of the IOC executive favored the Austrian bid as a way to "make peace with the people of Austria" over the decision in 1972 to declare Austrian skiing star Karl Schranz ineligible for the games as a professional athlete.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Undeterred, Lake Placid re-sent the same campaign materials that were originally used for the 1976 bid to the United States Olympic Committee on November 20, 1973, and made the official bid in September 1974.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The United States Olympic Committee, embarrassed by Denver's 1976 withdrawal, required Lake Placid's bid to be widely supported by residents and government.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Lake Placid also secured the support of the environmental groups Sierra Club and Adirondack Mountain Club.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Three other cities declared themselves candidates for the 1980 Winter Games: Vancouver—Garibaldi (Canada), Lahti (Finland), and Chamonix (France).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The bids for Lahti and Chamonix were withdrawn early in the bid process, and Vancouver (the latter hosted the 2010 games), which was unable to obtain the support of the Government of British Columbia, withdrew its candidacy on October 4, 1974.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The members of the IOC awarded the 1980 Winter Games to Lake Placid on October 23, 1974, during the 75th IOC Session in Vienna.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The Lake Placid Games took place in the shadow of the Cold War with a number of other complex international events occurring in the leadup to the games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] In November 1979, sixty-two Americans were taken hostage at the United States embassy in Tehran by Iranian militants, a situation that would not resolve until after the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] In December 1979, the Soviet Union began the invasion of Afghanistan, which led to United States President Jimmy Carter calling for the international boycott of the 1980 Summer Games in Moscow.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The Western governments first considered the idea of boycotting the Moscow 1980 Summer Olympics in response to the situation in Afghanistan at the December 20, 1979, meeting of NATO representatives.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The idea was not completely new to the world: in the mid-1970s, proposals for an Olympic boycott circulated widely among human rights activists and groups as a sanction for Soviet violations of human rights.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] At that time, very few member governments expressed interest in the proposal.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] However, the idea gained popularity in early January 1980 when Soviet nuclear scientist and dissident Andrei Sakharov called for a boycott.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] On January 14, 1980, the Carter Administration joined Sakharov's appeal and set a deadline by which the Soviet Union must pull out of Afghanistan or face the consequences, including an international boycott of the games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] On January 26, 1980, Canadian Prime Minister Joe Clark announced that Canada, like the US, would boycott the Olympic Games if Soviet forces did not leave Afghanistan by February 20, 1980.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Carter also proposed moving the Olympics to Greece on a permanent basis to eliminate the issue of politicization of the Games' hosting, but the IOC rejected the idea.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Ultimately, 66 nations boycotted the 1980 Summer Olympics, but this did not impact the Lake Placid Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Another ongoing international situation was the conflict between the People's Republic of China and Taiwan.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Taiwan competed under the name of "Republic of China" and with its national flag until the 1976 Winter Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] In October 1979, the IOC recognized the Olympic Committee of the People's Republic of China after threats from China to withdraw from the Games, and forced Taiwan to take the name "Chinese Taipei" and to adopt a new flag for the 1980 Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The decision was appealed to a Swiss court and was upheld on January 15, 1980.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The Taiwanese delegation refused to comply with the IOC's decision and arrived at the Olympic Village with the same flag and the same name as before.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] After being refused entry, the Taiwan team canceled its participation in the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The People's Republic of China, which threatened to withdraw if Taiwan participated under the name of "Republic of China", took part in its first Olympic Games since 1952 and the first Winter Games in its history.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The Lake Placid Olympic Organizing Committee (LPOOC) was established as a not-for-profit corporation in December 1974.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Its board of directors was made up of 48 people, with a 13-member executive board.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Ron MacKenzie, who was instrumental in developing the region and securing the Games, was the chair of the organizing committee when it was founded.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] He died in December 1978, fourteen months before the start of the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Bernard Fell was the chairman of the board of directors and Art Devlin was the vice-chairman.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The LPOOC's vision for the Games was a simple Games that would return to the basics of the Olympic movement.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The budget for the 1980 Winter Olympic Games grew from an initial projection of US$30 million, to a total of US$168.7 million.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The cost of the games was financed by three parties, the federal government ($82.7 million), the State of New York ($32.4 million), and the organizing committee ($53.6 million).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] In the 2016 study of cost overruns at Olympic Games at Oxford University, researchers found the Lake Placid Winter Olympic Games had the largest cost overruns of any Winter Games at 324 percent above the planned cost.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The budget overruns were attributed to environmental protection measures, additional work undertaken to modernize existing facilities, overly optimistic cost estimates, and inflation.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The Games ended with a deficit of $8.5 million.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] After a request for funds and the authorities' refusal, the organizing committee saw no other option but to declare bankruptcy, but in January 1981 the Governor of New York announced that the remaining deficit would be paid by New York State.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Additional costs included transport improvements totaling $4.8 million, the extension of the electricity and hydroelectric network at $2.7 million, and construction for the headquarters of the New York State Police at $3.8 million.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] In addition, $8 million was allocated for security costs.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The expenses of the organizing committee were mainly administrative totaling $48.1 million.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The increasing costs for the Games and charges of nepotism and mismanagement resulted in a federal auditor investigating the LPOOC.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Public questions regarding accounting practices and contract awards resulted in the LPOOC's marketing director being replaced.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Further scrutiny came when another director was asked to resign when it became public that the individual had not filed income taxes for a number of years.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The company awarded the food management contract for the Games came under federal investigation for associations with organized crime.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Revenue for the LPOOC came primarily from sponsorship contracts signed with more than 200 companies totaling around $30 million in cash, goods or services, and from the sale of broadcasting rights totaling $21 million and included $8 million donated to the IOC.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Around 550,000 tickets were distributed for the 1980 Winter Olympic Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Ticket distribution to the public included different regions of the United States (65.8%), Canada (6%), and other countries (8.2%).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The remainder was distributed among sponsors and suppliers (8.7%), the US Olympic Committee, the organizing committee, authorities, donors, and authorized companies (10.1%), or kept in reserve (1.2%).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The public prices for tickets ranged from $15 to $70.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Security for the Lake Placid Winter Games was provided by the New York State Police and 26 other agencies including the Federal Bureau of Investigation.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The organizing committee also hired the private security company Pinkerton National Detective Agency.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The security headquarters were located at Ray Brook, which also was the site of the Olympic Village.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Police officers were trained in hostage negotiation techniques and various sensors were installed to detect any terrorist attack.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] A four-meter double barrier was erected surrounding the Olympic Village.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The Lake Placid Winter Games were plagued with transportation problems complicating the planning and operations of the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The small mountain community did not have the accommodations or resources to handle the expected 50,000 spectators each day.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Most of the accommodations within the community were reserved for Games officials and athletes' families, meaning spectators commuted as much as ninety miles (140 km) daily to attend events.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Anticipating these challenges, the LPOOC prohibited private cars from entering Lake Placid for the duration of the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Instead the LPOOC provided parking and a shuttle system to transport spectators to the competition venues, and hired 60 taxis and 300 coaches, instead of the 450 initially planned, to be available to athletes, coaches, officials, and VIPs.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The first evidence that the Games would be plagued with transportation issues came a year earlier, at the pre-Olympic ski jumping competition in February 1979, which saw spectators create an eleven-mile (18 km) traffic jam.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Once the Games started, the inadequate transportation planning was evident quickly as American and Soviet athletes arrived late for the opening ceremony.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Throughout the Games, the main street of Lake Placid was often blocked by traffic jams, and journalists, spectators, and athletes found long waits at bus stops.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Spectators were often left stranded, either missing events or unable to return home from events.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] After five days, Governor Hugh Carey declared a partial state of emergency to address the issues.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The LPOOC attributed the transportation challenges to, among other things, the lack of communication with transport companies and the state government.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The emblem of the 1980 Olympic Winter Games contained several symbols.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The right part was reminiscent of the mountains surrounding Lake Placid and the left part was a stylized Ionic column that referred to the Ancient Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The indentation at the top of the column represented two basins symbolizing the two editions of the Games organized in Lake Placid.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] On the Games poster, the Olympic rings overhung this emblem.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The former Will Rogers Memorial Hospital was briefly used as press headquarters.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The site was considered ideal for the available infrastructure from the 1932 Winter Olympics, most notably the Bobsleigh run.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The existing facilities meant the Olympics could be staged on a reasonable budget and with limited environmental impact.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] It was not just a matter of convenience, either, according to Lake Placid's congressman, Representative Robert McEwen.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] "It is no secret to us in America that the measure of federal support given to athletes in Communist countries (so that they win medals and improve the countries' image abroad) is on a level unknown to us here in America," he told Congress.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The local Olympic committee needed congressional approval for funding to build the Olympic Village.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Congress required an after-use contract for facilities, and it was agreed that the Olympic Village would be built in accordance to Federal Bureau of Prisons needs.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Following the Olympic Games, it was repurposed for Federal Correctional Institution, Ray Brook.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1980 Winter Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Cyprus made its Olympic debut at the games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The People's Republic of China and Costa Rica both made their Winter Olympic debut.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The Republic of China refused to attend both the Summer Games in Montreal, the Winter Games in Lake Placid, and the Summer Games in Moscow over the IOC's recognition of the People's Republic of China as "China", and its request for the Republic of China to compete as "Chinese Taipei".
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The PRC, on the other hand, returned to the Olympics for the first time since 1952 and made its Winter Olympic debut, although it then boycotted the 1980 Moscow Summer Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] Roni was the Olympic mascot of the Games, created by Don Moss.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The mascot was a raccoon, which is a familiar animal from the mountainous region of the Adirondacks where Lake Placid is situated.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The name Roni came from the word *raccoon* in Iroquoian, the language of the native people from the region of the State of New York and Lake Placid, and was chosen by Lake Placid school children.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/1980-winter-olympics] The official theme song for the 1980 Winter Olympics was "Give It All You Got" by the American flugelhorn player Chuck Mangione, who performed the song (along with the song "Piña Colada") live at the Closing Ceremony, with the Hamilton Philharmonic Orchestra (Canada).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Salt Lake City was selected as the host city in June 1995 at the 104th IOC Session.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] They were the eighth Olympics to be hosted by the United States, and the most recent to be held in the country until 2028, when Los Angeles will host the 34th Summer Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The 2002 Winter Olympics and Paralympics were both organized by the Salt Lake Organizing Committee (SLOC), the first time that both events were organized by a single committee, and inspiring other Olympic and Paralympic Games to be organized by such since then.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] These were the first Olympic Games under the International Olympic Committee (IOC) presidency of Jacques Rogge.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The Games featured 2,399 athletes from 78 nations, participating in 78 events in 15 disciplines.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Norway topped the medal table, with 13 gold and 25 medals overall, while Germany finished with the most total medals, winning 36 (with 12 of them gold).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The hosting United States was third by gold medals and second by overall medals, with 10 and 34 respectively.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Australia notably became the first Southern Hemisphere country to ever win gold medals at the Winter Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The Games finished with a budgetary surplus of US$40 million; the surplus was used to fund the formation of the Utah Athletic Foundation—which has continued to maintain the facilities built for these Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The venues have continued to be used for national and international winter sports events after the Olympics, leading to the Winter Olympics return to Salt Lake City for the 2034 games, 32 years after the city played host in 2002.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Salt Lake City was chosen over Québec City, Canada; Sion, Switzerland; and Östersund, Sweden, on June 16, 1995, at the 104th IOC Session in Budapest, Hungary.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Salt Lake City had previously come in second during the bids for the 1998 Winter Olympics, awarded to Nagano, Japan, and had offered to be the provisional host of the 1976 Winter Olympics when the original host, Denver, Colorado, withdrew.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The 1976 Winter Olympics were ultimately awarded to Innsbruck, Austria.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] There was a scandal involving allegations of bribery used to win the rights to the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Prior to its successful bid, Salt Lake City had attempted four times to secure the games, failing each time.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] In 1998, members of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) were accused of taking gifts from the Salt Lake Organizing Committee (SLOC) during the bidding process.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The allegations resulted in the expulsion of several IOC members and the adoption of new IOC rules.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Although nothing strictly illegal had been done, it was felt that the acceptance of the gifts was morally dubious.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] In addition, legal charges were brought against the leaders of Salt Lake's bid committee by the United States Department of Justice.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Investigations were also launched into prior bidding process by other cities, finding that members of the IOC received bribes during the bidding process for both the 1998 Winter Olympics and 2000 Summer Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] In response to the scandal, Mitt Romney was hired as the new president and CEO of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee in February 1999.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] In February 1999, in response to the bid scandal and a financial shortfall for the Games, Mitt Romney, then CEO of the private equity firm Bain Capital (and future U.S. presidential candidate, U.S.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Senator, and Governor of Massachusetts), was hired as the new president and CEO of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] An additional US$410 million was received from the federal government.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] U.S. federal subsidies amounted to $1.3 billion (for infrastructure improvements only), compared to $45 billion of federal funding received by the organizing committee of the 2014 Winter Olympics from the Russian government.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The Games were financially successful, raising more money with fewer sponsors than any prior Olympic Games, which left SLOC with a surplus of $40 million.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The surplus was used to create the Utah Athletic Foundation, which maintains and operates many of the remaining Olympic venues.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The 2002 Winter Games were the first Olympic Games to take place since the September 11 attacks, which meant a higher level of security than ever before provided for the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] As a result, the Office of Homeland Security (OHS) designated the Olympics a National Special Security Event (NSSE).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Aerial surveillance and radar control was provided by the U.S.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Marines of Marine Air Control Squadron 2, Detachment C, from Cherry Point, North Carolina.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The FBI and NSA arranged with Qwest Communications to use intercept equipment for a period of less than six months around the time of the 2002 Winter Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The largest public transport project completed for the Games was the TRAX light rail system, which first began operations ahead of the Games in 1999.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] To help reduce vehicle traffic to Soldier Hollow, and to provide a tourist attraction for attendees, Heber Valley Railroad offered service to Wasatch Mountain State Park on steam locomotives during the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] After arriving, passengers then embarked to Soldier Hollow on horse-drawn sleighs.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Work on venues for the 2002 Winter Olympics began as early as 1989, following the passing of a state referendum that authorized the use of taxpayer money to publicly fund the construction of new facilities for a Winter Olympics bid in 1998 or 2002.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Their construction was overseen by the Salt Lake Olympic Bid Committee and the Utah Sports Authority—a body created under the referendum.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] New facilities built for the Games included the Utah Olympic Oval in Kearns, Utah Olympic Park in Summit County, The Ice Sheet at Ogden, and Soldier Hollow at the Wasatch Mountain State Park—the furthest competition venue from Salt Lake City.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The E Center in West Valley City and the Peaks Ice Arena in Provo were also built with support from the SLOC, and co-hosted hockey.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Delta Center hosted figure skating and short track speed skating; it was renamed *Salt Lake Ice Center* for the duration of the Games due to IOC sponsorship rules.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Rice-Eccles Stadium at the University of Utah hosted the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The Olympic Village was built at historic Fort Douglas, whose land had been acquired by the University of Utah to construct new residences.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The SLOC provided funding to the project in exchange for its use during the Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Main Street in Park City was converted into a pedestrian plaza during the Games, with festivities such as concerts, firework shows, and sponsor presences.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Medal presentations took place in downtown Salt Lake City; the stage for the ceremony featured the Hoberman Arch, an arch-shaped metal "curtain" designed by Chuck Hoberman.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The 2002 Cultural Olympiad, which ran from January to March 2002, was an arts festival that accompanied the 2002 Winter Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] It included specially commissioned works, such as Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater's work *Here...Now* inspired by the life of Olympian Florence Griffith Joyner, accompanied by music by Wynton Marsalis.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] An art exhibition was held at Springville Museum of Art that celebrated 150 years of Utah's art history.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The programme also featured many other performances, including dance, theatre, singing, and literature, as well as the glass art of Dale Chihuly.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Call of the Champions is a cantata-fanfare for orchestra and choir composed by John Williams for the 2002 Winter Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Premiering at the Opening Ceremony on February 8, 2002, it began with the call by the Tabernacle Choir at Temple Square of "Citius!
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Fortius!" (Faster, Higher, Stronger), which is the Olympic Motto chosen by the founder of the modern Games, Baron Pierre de Coubertin.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The torch relay ceremonially began on November 19, 2001, with the traditional kindling of an Olympic flame in Olympia, Greece.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] On December 3, Greek skier Thanassis Tsailas lit the first torch from the cauldron, and transferred its flame to a ceremonial lantern for transport to Atlanta, where it arrived on December 4 to officially launch the U.S. leg of the relay.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The route of the relay covered 13,500 miles (21,700 km), passed through 300 communities and 46 U.S. states, and was carried by 12,012 torchbearers.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The torch was modeled after an icicle, with a slight curve to represent speed and fluidity.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The torch measures 33 inches (84 cm) long, 3 inches (7.6 cm) wide at the top, 0.5 inches (1.3 cm) at the bottom, and was designed by Axiom Design of Salt Lake City.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] It was created with three sections, each with its own meaning and representation.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The overall branding of the 2002 Winter Olympics, the "Look of the Games" design was named "Land of Contrast — Fire and Ice", which featured a palette of warm and cool colors to contrast the warmer, rugged, red-rock areas of Southern Utah from the colder, mountainous regions of Northern Utah.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The three main color palettes were: *Amber Gold*, *Sunset Orange* and *Mountain Shadow Blue*: With accented hue variations of the palette.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] It featured a six pointed snow crystal, again with the three main colors representing Utahs southern deserts and its high snowy mountain ranges.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Designed to resemble an Olympic cauldron, a flame, as well as a sun rising from behind mountains.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The orange center section of the flame was intended to reflect traditional Navajo weaving.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The emblem logo was designed by Landor Associates and unveiled in August 1997.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The official event pictograms were inspired by branding irons, and the line thickness and 30-degree angles mirrored those of the emblem.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The designs of the mascots of the 2002 Winter Olympics were unveiled on May 19, 1999, during an event marking 1,000 days until the opening ceremony.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] For the first time in Olympic history, the names of the mascots were determined by a public vote, using name suggestions submitted by local students; on September 25, the names of the mascots were officially announced as Powder, Copper, and Coal respectively.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] A total of 78 teams qualified at least one athlete to compete in the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Five NOCs made their Winter Olympic debut in Salt Lake, including Cameroon, Hong Kong, Nepal, Tajikistan, and Thailand.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Costa Rica and Lebanon returned to the Winter games after a 10-year absence, and Fiji, Mexico and San Marino returned after 8 years.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Four countries, Luxembourg, North Korea, Portugal and Uruguay which were at the 1998 Games, did not participate in 2002.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] In the following calendar for the 2002 Winter Olympic Games, each blue box represents an event competition, such as a qualification round, on that day.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The yellow boxes represent days during which medal-awarding finals for a sport are held.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The number in each box represents the number of finals that were contested on that day.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The opening ceremony of the 2002 Winter Olympics was held at Rice–Eccles Stadium at the University of Utah on February 8, 2002.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The facility was renovated and expanded for the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The Games were officially opened by President George W.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The flag was presented during the playing of the U.S. national anthem "The Star-Spangled Banner", as performed by the Tabernacle Choir.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The Olympic cauldron was designed to look like an icicle and was made of glass, allowing the fire to be seen burning within, reflecting the Games' slogan "Light the Fire Within" and an overarching "fire and ice" theme.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The actual glass cauldron stands atop a twisting glass and steel support, is 12 feet (3.7 m) high, and the flame within burns at 900 °F (482 °C).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Together with its support, the cauldron stands 117 feet (36 m) tall and was made of 738 individual pieces of glass.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Small jets send water down the glass sides of the cauldron to keep the glass and metal cooled (so they would not crack or melt) and give the effect of melting ice.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The cauldron was designed by WET Design of Los Angeles, its frame built by roller coaster manufacturer Arrow Dynamics of Clearfield, Utah, and its glass pieces created by Western Glass of Ogden, Utah.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The cauldron's cost was $2 million, and it was unveiled to the public when originally installed at Rice–Eccles Stadium on January 8, 2002.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Production for the opening and closing ceremonies was designed by Seven Nielsen, and music for both ceremonies was directed by Mark Watters.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The closing ceremony of the 2002 Winter Olympics was held on February 24, 2002, at Rice–Eccles Stadium.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Kelly, Sting, Willie Nelson, and Yo Yo Ma.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] It also featured appearances by figure skaters such as Kurt Browning, Dorothy Hamill, and Ilia Kulick, as well as dancer Savion Glover.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Departing from Juan Antonio Samaranch's tradition of declaring each Olympics the "best ever", IOC president Jacques Rogge began a tradition of assigning each Games their own identity in his comments, describing the 2002 Winter Olympics as having been "flawless".
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Italian singers Irene Grandi and Elisa performed during the cultural presentation by Turin, host city of the 2006 Winter Olympics, while Josh Groban and Charlotte Church performed a duet of "The Prayer" as the Olympic cauldron was extinguished.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Confirmed in 1997, this edition's sports program featured seven sports divided into 15 disciplines, totaling 78 events, an increase of 10 events over the 1998 Winter Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Skeleton made its return to the Winter Olympic program for the first time since 1948, while a women's doubles event was contested for the first time in bobsleigh.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] A fourth distance was introduced in short track speed skating for men and women, and the pursuit events were added to biathlon and cross-country skiing.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The sprint event was also added to the Nordic combined program.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] At the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City, the "medal plaza" was popularized as a way for the public to see presentations that would have otherwise taken place at far-flung, low-capacity or high-altitude venues and to have an evening program that often included musical performances.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] International Sports Broadcasting (ISB) served as the host broadcaster for the 2002 Winter Olympics; the Salt Palace convention center served as the International Broadcast Centre and press center for the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The IOC estimated that the 2002 Winter Olympics were viewed by over two billion people worldwide, with 13 billion viewer-hours watched.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] In the United States, the 2002 Winter Olympics were broadcast by NBC Universal networks.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] They were the first Winter Olympics under a multi-year rights agreement between NBC and the IOC, under which it would hold exclusive rights to all Olympic Games from 1996 through 2008.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The contract had excluded the 1998 Winter Olympics, as CBS Sports had an existing deal to exclusively televise the Winter Olympics from 1992 through 1998.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] NBC partnered with HDNet to produce an eight-hour block of daily coverage in high definition, which was carried by HDNet and on the digital signals of participating NBC affiliates.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Coverage of the Games by the Seven Network in Australia featured *The Ice Dream*, a miniseries presented by comedy duo Roy and HG as a follow-up to *The Dream*—their series for the 2000 Summer Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The series featured a running gag of the duo proposing an Australian bid to hold the 2010 Winter Olympics in the resort town of Smiggin Holes, New South Wales.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The 2002 Winter Olympics brought a huge amount of success to the Utah skiing industry.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Since hosting the Winter Games, Utah has seen a 42% increase in skier and snowboarder visits as of 2010–11.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] This increase resulted in direct expenditures from skiers and snowboarders growing 67% from $704 million in 2002–2003 to $1.2 billion in 2010–2011.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Fourteen venues were constructed or expanded in preparation for the Winter Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] One of the venues constructed for the Games was the Utah Olympic Park, which has proven to be one of the most successful venues to date because it has been maintained in top competition form.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Owing to the routine maintenance of the park, Utah has been able to host a large number of winter competitions since 2002, including more than 60 World Cup events (e.g. the FIS Freestyle Skiing World Cup), as well as seven world championships, and various other sporting events.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Hosting these high-profile competitions has resulted in approximately $1 billion being injected into the local economy.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] During 2013–2014, Utah held 16 various winter sport events, bringing $27.3 million to the economy of Utah.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] After holding the Olympics, Utah became home to two National Governing Bodies of Sport.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Ski and Snowboard Association is headquartered in Park City, Utah and the U.S.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Olympic speed skating team is based out of the Utah Olympic Oval.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The University of Utah was one of the hosts of the 2002 Winter Olympics; the planning committee approached the University of Utah and asked them to build several student dormitories which would serve as athletes' accommodation during the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] It was agreed that the university would pay approximately $98 million out of the total required amount of $110 million to complete the construction.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] As a result, students of the university have benefited as almost 3,500 of them would be housed here after the Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] This was a great economic benefit to the university since the amount of money used to complete such dormitories could take long to be afforded.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The university was also asked to expand Rice Eccles Stadium to accommodate 50,000 people up from 32,000.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The university would then be refunded almost $59 million and be given an extra $40 million for its maintenance.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The 2002 Olympic Games also benefited the university economically since the Salt Lake 2002 Olympic Cauldron Park was elevated by the renovations that took place.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Ice rinks were very scarce in Utah, but they became plentiful and offered several entertainment and training opportunities for hockey players and figure skaters due to the Olympic Games.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Besides, the park had 17 plates that hung on the stadium's fence celebrating the highlights of each day of the Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] All these features acted as tourist attraction that boosted the economic development of the university.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] In addition, it is indicated that the approximate value of media exposure through print during the Games was equated to $22.9 million.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Mainly, this was a huge economic benefit to the university as more and more people got to know about the educational establishment, and this also boosted enrollment and future development.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] It was noted that the increase of Olympic related job started in 1996 and continued until 2003.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] These effects can be estimated on the ground of historical relationship between job and corresponding population growth.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] A lot of people migrated into the future place of the Olympic Games for expanding and favorable employment opportunities that the Olympics ensured.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Although residents occupied many of the higher paying jobs created by the Games, many of the vacated jobs were filled by immigrants who relocated for the better employment opportunities.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Basically, the immigration rate was even larger because the employees immigrated with their families.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The additional people paid diverse taxes and fees from their income, creating additional revenue on the state and local levels.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Olympic related jobs in Utah started in 1996 with slight job opportunities of less than 100.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] However, from the job measurement conducted from 1996 to 2002, steady attainment of job opportunities established and a maximum level was noted in 2001 where there were 12,500 job opportunities attained yearly, and approximately 25,070 jobs created in 2002.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Therefore, from 1996 to 2002 the sum of employment equated to 35,000 jobs which lasted a year.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] February 2002 is when the highest employment opportunities were created compared to other years.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] There were around 25,070 job opportunities created compared to 35,000 created from 1996 to 2001.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] It is difficult to quantify the impact of the 2002 Olympics on the unemployment rates in Utah, due mostly to the effect of the early 2000s recession.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] In 1996, the unemployment rate in Utah was approximately 3.4%, while the U.S. national average was 5.4% and by the end of 2001, the unemployment rate in Utah was around 4.8%, while the national average had risen to 5.7%.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] There was a high percentage of visitors to the Games, which raised the number of tourists whose consumption and demand prompted the establishment of job opportunities to meet the demands.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] In 2017, an exploratory committee was formed to consider a Salt Lake City bid for a future Winter Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] In December 2018, the United States Olympic Committee (USOC, now the United States Olympic & Paralympic Committee [USOPC]) named Salt Lake City as its preferred candidate to bid for a future Winter Olympics, citing that its experience and existing venues could be leveraged.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] On July 24, 2024, during the 142nd IOC Session in Paris just before the 2024 Summer Olympics in that city, Salt Lake City–Utah was selected to host the 2034 Winter Olympics and Paralympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] IOC President Thomas Bach said: "Salt Lake City and Utah are long-time friends of the Olympic Movement, and we are confident that they will organize exceptional Olympic and Paralympic Games, just as they did years ago.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The legacy of 2002 is tangibly and passionately alive in Utah.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The legacy of 2034 starts today." With the 2034 Winter Olympics, Salt Lake City will become the fourth city to host multiple Winter Games after Innsbruck (1964 and 1976), Lake Placid (1932 and 1980), and Cortina d'Ampezzo (1956 and 2026).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The 2002 Winter Olympics were the first Winter Olympics held after the formation of the World Anti-Doping Agency, resulting in the first instances of athletes being disqualified for failing drug testing.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Athletes in cross-country skiing were disqualified for various reasons, including doping by two Russians and one Spaniard, leading Russia to file protests and threaten to withdraw from the competition.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] A major scandal emerged during the pairs figure skating competition; the Canadian pair of Jamie Salé and David Pelletier narrowly lost to the Russian pair of Elena Berezhnaya and Anton Sikharulidze, despite the Canadians being deemed the favorites to win after their free skate program.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The French judge Marie-Reine Le Gougne alleged that the head of the French Federation of Ice Sports, Didier Gailhaguet, had pressured her to judge the competition in favor of Russia regardless of performance.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] They also recommended to the IOC that the gold medal be jointly awarded to both pairs.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] An IOC panel voted in favor of the motion, resulting in both Salé and Pelletier, as well as Berezhnaya and Sikharulidze, being jointly awarded gold medals.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] In the final race A, with one lap remaining and currently in second place, Apolo Ohno of the United States attempted to make a pass on the leader Kim Dong-Sung of South Korea, who then drifted to the inside and as a result, Ohno raised his arms to imply he was blocked.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] Kim finished first ahead of Ohno, but the Australian referee James Hewish disqualified Kim for what appeared to be impeding, awarding the gold medal to Ohno.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The South Korean team immediately protested the decision of the chief official of the race, but their protests were denied by the International Skating Union (ISU).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The South Korean team then appealed to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and the Court of Arbitration for Sport (CAS).
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The IOC refused to see the case, stating, "This is a matter for the ISU to decide on.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] At this time, the IOC has received no proposal and taken no action".
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The disqualification of Kim upset South Korean supporters, many of whom directed their anger at Ohno and the IOC.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] A large number of e-mails protesting the race results crashed the IOC's email server, and thousands of accusatory letters, many of which contained death threats, were sent to Ohno and the IOC.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] South Korean media accused Ohno of simulating foul, using the Konglish word "Hollywood action".
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] The controversy continued at the 2002 FIFA World Cup, held jointly in South Korea and Japan several months after the Olympics.
[src:1972-denver-winter-olympics-referendum/2002-winter-olympics] When the South Korean soccer team scored a goal during the group stage match against the U.S. team, South Korean players Ahn Jung-Hwan and Lee Chun-Soo made an exaggerated move imitating the move Ohno had made during the speed skating event to imply the other athlete had drifted into his lane.
